 #include <stdio.h>
        int main()
        {
            char *a[2] = {"hello", "hi"};
            printf("%s\n", *(a + 1));
            return 0;
        }
////////////////////////////////////////////////
1️⃣ Understanding the declaration
char *a[2] = {"hello", "hi"};

This means:

a is an array of 2 pointers to char

Memory representation:

a[0] → "hello"
a[1] → "hi"

Each element stores the address of the first character of the string literal.

Example layout:

Stack
------------------
a[0] → address of "hello"
a[1] → address of "hi"

Read-only memory
------------------
"h e l l o \0"
"h i \0"
2️⃣ What a represents
Array name a behaves like a pointer to its first element:

a → &a[0]
So:
a + 1 → &a[1]
3️⃣ Understanding *(a + 1)
*(a + 1)

Step by step:

a + 1      → address of a[1]
*(a + 1)   → value stored in a[1]

But a[1] contains a pointer to the string "hi".

So:

*(a + 1) == a[1] == "hi"
4️⃣ printf statement
printf("%s\n", *(a + 1));

%s prints a string starting from that pointer.

Since:
*(a + 1) → "hi"

the program prints: hi

5️⃣ Equivalent expressions

These are all the same:
*(a + 1)
a[1]

7️⃣ Key concept tested in interviews
a[i] == *(a + i)
This applies to arrays of pointers as well.
